<item>
            <title>[KAFKA-2335] Javadoc for Consumer says that it&apos;s thread-safe</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-2335</link>
                <project id="12311720" key="KAFKA">Kafka</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;This looks like it was left there by mistake:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The consumer is thread safe but generally will be used only from within a single thread. The consumer client has no threads of it&apos;s own, all work is done in the caller&apos;s thread when calls are made on the various methods exposed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A few paragraphs below it says:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Kafka consumer is NOT thread-safe. All network I/O happens in the thread of the application making the call. It is the responsibility of the user to ensure that multi-threaded access is properly synchronized. Un-synchronized access will result in &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;Unknown macro: {@link ConcurrentModificationException}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This matches what the code does, so the former quoted section should probably be deleted.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
